# ===============================
# MMIO vs DMA
# ===============================

# 1. OVERVIEW
# ------------
# MMIO (Memory-Mapped I/O):
# - CPU communicates directly with device registers by reading/writing memory addresses.
# - Best suited for small control/status operations.
# - CPU is actively involved in every read/write operation.

# DMA (Direct Memory Access):
# - Device transfers data directly to/from system memory without CPU intervention.
# - Best suited for large bulk data transfers.
# - CPU is free to perform other tasks while DMA handles the transfer.

# -------------------------------
# 2. DATA FLOW
# -------------------------------
# MMIO:
# CPU <--> Device
# Each read/write operation is done by the CPU.
# Example: CPU writes to control register or reads status register.

# DMA:
# Device <--> Memory
# CPU initiates DMA transfer (configures source, destination, size), then can continue other work.
# Example: DMA moves large network packet to kernel buffer without CPU copying.

# -------------------------------
# 3. SPEED
# -------------------------------
# MMIO:
# - Low latency for small transfers (control/status).
# - Poor for bulk transfers because CPU handles every byte/word.
# - CPU is busy during the entire transfer.

# DMA:
# - High throughput for large transfers.
# - CPU overhead minimal; transfer occurs asynchronously.
# - Reduces memory copy operations (user<->kernel<->device).

# -------------------------------
# 4. CPU INVOLVEMENT
# -------------------------------
# MMIO:
# - CPU directly reads/writes data.
# - Each access consumes CPU cycles.
# - Not scalable for high-throughput devices.

# DMA:
# - CPU sets up transfer, then DMA controller handles it.
# - CPU free to execute other tasks.
# - Ideal for network, storage, or graphics devices.

# -------------------------------
# 5. USAGE SCENARIOS
# -------------------------------
# MMIO:
# - Device initialization.
# - Setting control registers.
# - Reading device status flags.
# - Small configuration data.

# DMA:
# - Copying large buffers (disk, network packets, framebuffers).
# - Zero-copy transfers from user-space to device.
# - High-speed streaming data.

# -------------------------------
# 6. SUMMARY
# -------------------------------
# + MMIO
#   - CPU involved in every access
#   - Low latency for small operations
#   - Inefficient for bulk data

# + DMA
#   - CPU initiates, then device transfers data autonomously
#   - Efficient for large data transfers
#   - Reduces CPU overhead and memory copying

# TIP:
# - Most high-performance drivers combine both:
#   * MMIO for control/status registers
#   * DMA for bulk data transfers

